# Gnusto Overview

- See [README.md](mdc:README.md) for an overview of the Gnusto project and its goals.

## Components

- Each component has its own file in `/Sources/Models/Components`.

## Command Handlers

- The `processCommand` function in [ActionDispatcher.swift](mdc:Sources/Gnusto/Services/ActionDispatcher.swift) hands off to a command handler.
- Each handler has its own file in `/Sources/Services/CommandHandlers`.

## Objects

Use public object initializers:

```swift
// Wrong:
let world = World()
var lantern = Object(id: "lantern")
lantern.add(DescriptionComponent(
    name: "brass lantern",
    description: "A sturdy brass lantern that's currently off."
))
lantern.add(ObjectComponent(flags: [.device, .takeable]))
lantern.add(LightSourceComponent(isOn: false))
lantern.add(LocationComponent(parent: "darkRoom"))
world.write(lantern)

// Right
let world = World()
Object.object(
    id: "lantern",
    name: "brass lantern",
    description: "A sturdy brass lantern that's currently off.",
    location: "darkRoom",
    flags: .device, .takeable,
    synonyms: "lamp",
    in: world,
    LightSourceComponent(isOn: false)
)
```

## Testing

- ALWAYS use Swift Testing. NEVER use XCTest.
- Throw `TestFailure`s when something expected isn't found, rather than using optionals:

```swift
// Wrong:
let chest = world.object("chest")
#expect(chest != nil)
let chestContainer = chest?.get(ContainerComponent.self)
#expect(chestContainer?.isOpen == false)

// Right:
guard let chest = world.object("chest") else {
    throw TestFailure("Failed to get chest")
}
guard let chestContainer = chest.get(ContainerComponent.self) else {
    throw TestFailure("Failed to get chest container component")
}
#expect(chestContainer.isOpen == false)
```

- Use `CustomDump.expectNoDifference` over `#expect(msg == "Hello world")` for string literal comparisons:

```swift
// Wrong:
#expect(renderer.flush() == "You turn on brass lantern.")

// Right:
expectNoDifference(renderer.flush(), "You turn on brass lantern.")
expectNoDifference(renderer.flush(), """
    A mysterious room with shimmering walls and a pedestal in the center.
    Exits: west
    You can see: Adventurer, stone pedestal
    """
)
```

- Use `Renderer.process(effects)` helper for more concise tests:

```swift
// Wrong:
let lookEffects = dispatcher.dispatch(.command(.look), in: world)
for effect in lookEffects {
    renderer.render(effect)
}

let output = renderer.flush()
#expect(output.contains("A spacious cave with ancient drawings on the walls."))

// Right:
let lookEffects = dispatcher.dispatch(.command(.look), in: world)
expectNoDifference(
    renderer.process(lookEffects),
    """
    A spacious cave with ancient drawings on the walls.
    You can see: wall torch
    """
)
```

## Style Guide

- Multi-parameter functions have one line per named parameter per:

```swift
// Wrong:
let playerRoom = Object(id: "room",
                        DescriptionComponent(name: "Test Room", description: "A simple test room."),
                        RoomComponent(isLit: false)  // Make it a dark room to test lighting
)

// Right:
let playerRoom = Object(
    id: "room",
    DescriptionComponent(
        name: "Test Room",
        description: "A simple test room."
    ),
    RoomComponent(isLit: false)  // Make it a dark room to test lighting
)

// Exception for short function signatures with unnamed param followed by named param:
let foo = Bar(.hello, world: true)  // This is fine
```

- Multiline `guard` conditions:

```swift
// Wrong:
guard let updatedLantern = world.object("lantern"),
      let lightSource = updatedLantern.get(LightSourceComponent.self) else {
    throw TestFailure("Failed to get lantern or light source component")
}

`` Right:
guard
    let updatedLantern = world.object("lantern"),
    let lightSource = updatedLantern.get(LightSourceComponent.self)
else {
    throw TestFailure("Failed to get lantern or light source component")
}
```